ags/閱讀/">閱讀</a></div></div></div><div class="main-content"><h4 id="Australia’s-bushfire-smoke-is-lapping-the-globe-and-the-law-is-too-lame-to-catch-it"><a href="#Australia’s-bushfire-smoke-is-lapping-the-globe-and-the-law-is-too-lame-to-catch-it" class="headerlink" title="Australia’s bushfire smoke is lapping the globe, and the law is too lame to catch it."></a>Australia’s bushfire smoke is lapping the globe, and the law is too lame to catch it.</h4><p><img src="https://images.theconversation.com/files/311521/original/file-20200123-162185-rkhhzb.jpg?ixlib=rb-1.1.0&rect=0%2C0%2C4913%2C2456&q=45&auto=format&w=1356&h=668&fit=crop" alt><br>source: The conversation</p>
<p>After reading this article, I understood it’s also important to put bushfire as part of the climate change laws. Although bushfire could be a natural disaster sometimes, the increasing of this incident is actually avoidable. </p>
<p>In the beginning of establishing laws and setting emission reduction standards for countries is to make sure each country would follow the regulations and achieve the goal together. However, human beings are short-sighted animals which only foresee the immediate benefits, so we chose economy than environment. Many governments have started to go on this path and compromised the deal of reducing emission. As a result, animals and human beings are suffering, we are losing a balance of living in the eco system, nature has rebounded in surprising ways that caught us off guard. </p>
<p>At this rate, soon we’ll experience a series of natural disaster while most of us are still enjoying living in a modern world. Fertile lands become desert, mountain become flat land for cash crop, lakes have no water, drought, deforestation, or soil erosion…</p>
<p>Although scientists and many people are trying to prevent things getting worse, we’re still not working hard enough.</p>
